<body><div class=WordSection1>
<div class="brand">📚 ENGLISH CODING · 영어코딩</div>
<h1>📝 WD003 Week 1 — English Worksheet</h1>
<p><strong>Topic:</strong> Brand Kit + Wireframe — Plan Before You Build · <strong>Course:</strong> Portfolio Site · <strong>Time:</strong> about 60 minutes</p>
<p>This week there is <strong>no code yet</strong>. Real designers do two things before they touch a computer: they decide how the site should <strong>feel</strong> (a <strong>brand kit</strong>) and they decide what goes <strong>where</strong> (a <strong>wireframe</strong>). You will do both, on paper. Planning first means less getting lost later.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>A portfolio site usually has these sections: <strong>Hero</strong>, <strong>About</strong>, <strong>Projects</strong>, <strong>Contact</strong>, and a <strong>Footer</strong>. You will arrange them, then decide what <em>yours</em> says about <em>you</em>.</p>
</blockquote>
<hr />
<h2>1 · Predict 🔮</h2>
<p>Read each plan below. Before you imagine the page, write what you think a visitor would see.</p>
<pre><code>[ Nav: Home / About / Projects / Contact ]
[ Hero: my name + one line ]
[ About: photo + a few sentences ]
[ Projects: 3 cards ]
[ Contact: a form ]
[ Footer ]
</code></pre>
<p><strong>A visitor lands at the top and scrolls down. List, in order, what they see.</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<pre><code>[ Hero ]
[ Contact ]
[ About ]
[ Projects ]
</code></pre>
<p><strong>This site puts Contact second, right after the Hero. Is that a good first impression? What would a visitor know about this person before they are asked to send a message?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<pre><code>[ Nav: Home / About / Projects / Contact ]
[ Hero ]
[ About ]
</code></pre>
<p><strong>The nav menu has four links, but the page only has a Hero and an About section. What happens when a visitor clicks "Projects"?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<hr />
<h2>2 · Spot the Bug 🐛</h2>
<p>Each plan below was meant to do something, but it does not quite work yet. Read what the plan is <strong>supposed</strong> to do, then rewrite it so it makes sense. After that, explain why the original was a problem.</p>
<p><strong>Bug A</strong> — This wireframe is supposed to introduce the person <em>before</em> showing their work. Right now the Projects come before anyone knows who made them.</p>
<pre><code>[ Hero ]
[ Projects ]
[ About ]
[ Contact ]
</code></pre>
<p><strong>Write the fixed order:</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Why was the original order a problem? Why does your order work better?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Bug B</strong> — A wireframe is supposed to use <strong>boxes and labels only</strong> — no colors, no finished text, no real photos. This one has jumped ahead.</p>
<pre><code>[ Hero: bright orange background, font is &quot;Pretendard Bold 64px&quot;,
  exact paragraph already written out, real photo placed ]
</code></pre>
<p><strong>Hint:</strong> a wireframe decides <em>position</em>, not <em>paint</em>. Strip it back.</p>
<p><strong>Write a proper wireframe label for the Hero:</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Why is it better to leave the colors and final text for later?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Bug C</strong> — Every section is supposed to have a clear <strong>label</strong> so you know what it is for. This plan has a mystery box.</p>
<pre><code>[ Nav ]
[ Hero ]
[ ??? ]
[ Footer ]
</code></pre>
<p><strong>Hint:</strong> name the box, and say what one thing it shows.</p>
<p><strong>Write the fixed plan:</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Why does naming every box now save you trouble later?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<hr />
<h2>3 · Design Your Brand Kit 🎨</h2>
<p>A <strong>brand kit</strong> is a small set of choices that make everything you build look like <em>you</em> made it. Big companies have one. Now you do too. Work through these steps on one sheet of paper — that page becomes your brand kit.</p>
<ol>
<li><strong>Pick three words</strong> that describe you (for example: <em>curious, funny, calm</em>). Every choice after this should match your words.</li>
<li><strong>Choose your colors.</strong> Pick one main color and one background color that fit your three words. A calm person and a loud person should not end up with the same colors.</li>
<li><strong>Choose your font style.</strong> You do not need a font name yet — just decide: rounded or sharp? thick or thin? Write a small sample of your name in that style.</li>
<li><strong>Write your name the way it will appear at the top of your site.</strong> That is your logo for now.</li>
</ol>
<p>Stuck for ideas? Designers share their work on sites like <strong>dribbble.com</strong> and <strong>pinterest.com</strong> — searching "portfolio website" there shows you hundreds of real designs, and noticing what you like trains your eye. One caution: these sites are the open internet, and anyone can post anything, so you may run into things that are off-topic or not for kids. Stay on your search, and if something looks wrong, close it and move on. And remember — you are there to get <em>inspired</em>, not to copy someone's design box for box.</p>
<p><strong>Write your brand kit below too: your three words, your colors, your font style.</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<hr />
<h2>4 · Draw Your Wireframe 📐</h2>
<p>Now decide what goes where. On paper, sketch your site as a column of boxes — one box per section, in the order a visitor will see them.</p>
<p>A good wireframe follows these rules:</p>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Boxes and labels only.</strong> No colors, no real photos, no finished sentences — that all comes later.</p>
<p><strong>Name every box.</strong> A box nobody can name is a box nobody needed.</p>
<p><strong>One short note per box</strong> saying what it shows — "3 project cards", "photo + intro".</p>
<p><strong>Neat enough that a stranger could read it.</strong> If someone else picked up your paper, could they tell what each part of your site is? That is the test.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Sketch your Hero, About, Projects, Contact and Footer, then explain your plan. Use these sentence starters — write 4 to 6 sentences total.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>The three words I picked for myself are …</p>
<p>I chose these colors because …</p>
<p>My Hero section will say …</p>
<p>In my About section, I want to tell visitors …</p>
<p>The hardest part of planning was …</p>
<p>If I had more time, I would add …</p>
</blockquote>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<hr />
<h2>5 · Record Your Walkthrough 🎥</h2>
<p>Now take a video on your phone (or a parent's phone) and walk through your plan. Talk through it like you are showing someone what your finished site <em>will</em> look like. Try to use these words: <strong>brand kit</strong>, <strong>wireframe</strong>, <strong>section</strong>, <strong>Hero</strong>, <strong>layout</strong>.</p>
<blockquote>
<ol>
<li>Hold up your brand kit. Read your three words and say why your colors fit them.</li>
<li>Hold up your wireframe and point to each section from top to bottom.</li>
<li>Say which section you are most excited to build.</li>
</ol>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>Write what you will say in your video.</strong> Use the space below to plan it before you record — you can read from it while filming.</p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<hr />
<h3>Submit ✅</h3>
<p>Send this worksheet + a photo or video of your brand kit and wireframe to teacher on KakaoTalk.</p>
<div class="footer">영어코딩 · <b>english-coding.co.uk</b></div>
</div></body></html>
